t: right;\" border=\"1\" width=\"125\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img style=\"float: right;\" src=\"{CCM:FID_14}\" alt=\"spock.jpg\" width=\"125\" height=\"113\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Figure 4. Now I feel like Spock reading observations from a tricorder.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>And now on to this experiment that I keep mentioning. I want to measure and observe the volume of merchandise and services being bought and sold in the bitcoin community to see if the bitcoins are actually starting to be used as on online currency. At the same time, I want to help unify the bitcoin stores together under a single location on the web. To that end, I&rsquo;ve decided to list the items in my database in a live feed that displays each entry for a few seconds. Each time someone clicks on an item to buy, they will be redirected to the appropriate bitcoin store. I&rsquo;ve setup the feed so that I can track each click to see if people are buying stuff. Over time, I hope to measure the number of people wanting to buy stuff with their bitcoins.&nbsp;<br /><br />The feed can be easily embedded into any webpage. It is my hope that people will continue to use the plugin so that I can track the clicks. In time, I will make my statistics and findings publicly available. Anyone who wants to add items to the feed may do so by contacting me, and there will be no fees for having their merchandise added. Now, get started with the experiment and start clicking on stuff that you can buy with bitcoins!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<script src=\"http://api.bitcoinbulletin.com/btceconomy\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>')
