e conclusion that first successful bitcoin store would be Craigslist -&nbsp; a logical assumption given that craigslist is the biggest of all garage sales. We began following the people on the site who were accepting bitcoins as the method of payment. We even started reposting craigslist offerings from these individuals to help promote the bitcoin economy &ndash; a tedious process indeed.<br /><br />A few months passed, and nothing really happened on craigslist. It was disappointing. Meanwhile, even more bitcoin stores opened up, but as was the case with each one of these stores, I could count their entire stock of merchandise on my fingers. Clearly, there was a need to unify these stores to create a shopping mall out of the hundreds of outlets. This was the motivation for beginning my experiment, which all started on a cold Friday night in the Windy City.</p>\r\n<table style=\"float: left; margin: 15px;\" width=\"150\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img style=\"float: left;\" src=\"{CCM:FID_13}\" alt=\"neo.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"146\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Figure 3. I feel like Neo once again as I fly through the lines of computer code.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>That night, I downloaded an open-source package for crawling and indexing the web. I added my own modifications to the code, and before I went to bed I had a large MySQL database of all the items for sale in the bitcoin community. I then used a PHP framework to generate HTML pages for all the entries in my database. I scrolled through the pages containing the entries in my database, and I saw I could buy just about everything I needed. Food, deodorant, shoes to go with the alpaca socks, and even a new laptop were all right in front of me in my database. It was impressive, and at that moment I realized that bitcoins could become something more than cryptographic keys traded at Mt Gox. <em>(So maybe it took me more than just one night to do all of this)</em></p>\r\n<table style=\"float: right; margin: 15px;\" width=\"125\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img style=\"float: right;\" src=\"{CCM:FID_14}\" alt=\"spock.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"203\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Figure 4. Now I feel like Spock reading observations from a tricorder.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>And now on to this experiment that I keep mentioning. I want to measure and observe the volume of merchandise and services being bought and sold in the bitcoin community to see if the bitcoins are actually starting to be used as on online currency. At the same time, I want to help unify the bitcoin stores together under a single location on the web. To that end, I&rsquo;ve decided to list the items in my database in a live feed that displays each entry for a few seconds. Each time someone clicks on an item to buy, they will be redirected to the appropriate bitcoin store. I&rsquo;ve setup the feed so that I can track each click to see if people are buying stuff. Over time, I hope to measure the number of people wanting to buy stuff with their bitcoins.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"margin-left: 135px; width: 450px;\">\r\n<script src=\"http://api.bitcoinbulletin.com/btceconomy\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The feed can be easily embedded into any webpage. It is my hope that people will continue to use the plugin so that I can track the clicks. In time, I will make my statistics and findings publicly available. Anyone who wants to add items to the feed may do so by contacting me, and there will be no fees for having their merchandise added. Now, get started with the experiment and start clicking on stuff that you can buy with bitcoins!</p>')
 ,(587,'<p><img style=\"float: right;\" src=\"{CCM:FID_8}\" alt=\"love_bitcoins.png\" width=\"128\" height=\"128\" />Bitcoins are one of the few true digital currencies in existence, and although the technology behind bitcoins is complex, the currency is simple to use. Bitcoins are unique in that they have been designed with security in mind, can be traded online as easily as emails are sent, and are decentralized so that no authority can undermine the transactions.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>So what do people use bitcoins for? Well, you can see from our <a title=\"Bitcoin Merchandise\" href=\"{CCM:CID_1}\">search page</a> that you can use bitcoins to buy essentially any commidity or service that you can buy with traditional money. In fact, there are hundreds of businesses that collectively offer tens of thousands of products, and these numbers grow each day at an exponential rate.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>So how do you get bitcoins? The first step is to download the bitcoin software. The program is easy to install. Once you install it, you will be given a bitcoin address. This is kind of like an email address that is for receiving money online. A typical bitcoin address looks something like ours (<em>1QE66n52DeBhNifskYX6XwQj8u8dE9mAG1)</em>. The bitcoin software may take awhile to sync with the rest of the bitcoin network. If you don\'t want to wait this long, you can use any of the online bitcoin wallet services, which will operate the bitcoin software for you, to quickly get you your first bitcoin address.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Once you have setup a bitcoin account, you can use the <a title=\"Get some free bitcoins\" href=\"http://freebitcoins.appspot.com/\">bitcoin faucet</a> to get your first&nbsp;<em>bit-change</em> for free. The bit-change will be sent to your account and saved on your computer (all coins are saved into a special file called the wallet file). If you want more bitcoins you will probably have to purchase them from an <a title=\"Directory of bitcoin exhanges.\" href=\"http://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Buying_bitcoins\">exchange</a>. The exchanges are websites where people buy and sell bitcoins. We suggest that you sign-up at an exchange now, because it typically can take up to a week to verify your account.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"float: left; margin-top: 8px; margin-right: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;\" src=\"{CCM:FID_9}\" alt=\"Screenshot.png\" width=\"398\" height=\"200\" />You can also use the bitcoin software to generate new bitcoins. Wait! You can just print off new money in this currency? Well, yes, but it becomes harder to generate new bitcoins as more and more are made. Bitcoins were designed like this on purpose, to ensure a limited supply of bitcoins. In fact, there is a limit on the total number of bitcoins that can be generated. We recommend against trying to generate new bitcoins, unless you have a high-end model computer. Otherwise, you may be waiting around for a long time.</p>')
